it makes me want to be alive, even if just for a short while, even if just to see how much farther i can burn before i’m finally smothered and can return my flame to its siblings once more.

fire is warm and comforting, but water is cold and sharp. it reawakens a need for heat and its bite ignited feelings long since extinguished. water does not douse, it fuels. it makes me want to burn brighter.

it pushes us forward and creates motion, but sometimes? the heat begins to die down, long estranged from its family. the rain makes me feel natural. makes me believe that i’m meant to be here; meant to carry my internal torch to whatever blaze is at the end.

that fire hides so often and sometimes feels that it’s all but gone out, with nothing but a shell of its old home remaining. but under rain, it is once again reminded that it is just as natural and profound as the elements outside its encasing. fire is the most human element.

each element interacting and awakening the other in their ageless and arcane dance. my skin may now long be cold, but inside, deep in my gut, i feel an ember. a fire inside, having been left in a smoldering pile of ash, being stoked back to life by its elemental siblings.

perhaps a dissatisfying realization, but none the less profound. my skin, ever the more wet and cold the longer i’m outside, feels more alive and human than it ever does under the sun. i feel no different than the greenery and earth around me.

nature is its most true state when the elements interact: sky sending water to the earth below. am i natural enough to be purified? the droplets land on my skin and each electric pulse to my brain reminds me that i’m alive.

water is something that purifies that which it touches, and the dynamics of nature are something that truly become apparent when the light drips of rain land on the leaves scattered on the ground; the earth beneath sipping on the sky’s gift like a nest of baby birds.

but the deep, gray clouds block out the blinding yellow and i can finally see the world around me, uninhibited. the droplets of water, as they fall from the heavens, awaken dank and earthy smells from beneath the top layer of foliage and reveal themselves to me.

i enjoy thinking about the weather and how different climates make me feel. i’ve been known to prefer rainy weather. some see it as dreary and others as a nuisance; i see it as comfort. when it’s gloomy, the sun is gone and no longer inhibits my vision and i can see clearly.
